repo.name: cython

body:
Analagous to "PyTuple_Pack" designed to be used in "slow" (i.e. module-level) code. The main thing this catches are lists used in "from something import name".

Also use `PyTuple_Pack` more thoroughly in module-level code. The slow attribute of SequenceNode was never being set. This probably affects tuples used in class construction like the bases tuple, which isn't a literal.

(Part of "looking at small marginal module-size gains" https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/4425)

comment_data.body:
There seems to be a related special case in the `generate_subexpr_disposal_code()` method further down.
Since we're implementing the list helper function ourselves, we could also consider letting it steal the item references. But that's an optimisation, not required here.
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -8179,10 +8182,21 @@ def generate_sequence_packing_code(self, code, target=None, plain=False):
                 else:
                     size_factor = ' * (%s)' % (c_mult,)
 
-        if self.type is tuple_type and (self.is_literal or self.slow) and not c_mult:
+        if ((self.type is tuple_type or self.type is list_type) and
+                (self.is_literal or self.slow) and
+                not c_mult and
+                len(self.args) > 0):

comment_data.body: You left out the multiply part that appears in the other condition. I'd rather have the whole condition extracted and reused than having it (partly) duplicated. It's really complex and (evidently) easy to forget about.
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -8267,7 +8268,9 @@ def generate_sequence_packing_code(self, code, target=None, plain=False):
     def generate_subexpr_disposal_code(self, code):
         if self.mult_factor and self.mult_factor.type.is_int:
             super().generate_subexpr_disposal_code(code)
-        elif self.type is tuple_type and (self.is_literal or self.slow):
+        elif ((self.type is tuple_type or self.type is list_type) and
+                (self.is_literal or self.slow) and
+                len(self.args) > 0):

comment_data.body: The `plain` argument to `generate_sequence_packing_code` makes it quite hard to reason about what we need to do in `generate_subexpr_disposal_code` so I just recorded what we actually did and based it on that.

comment_data.body:
We always need some kind of cleanup, but not always disposal/decrefs.
```suggestion
    needs_subexpr_disposal = False  # set to True in code-generation if we
```

@@ -8052,6 +8052,10 @@ class SequenceNode(ExprNode):
     unpacked_items = None
     mult_factor = None
     slow = False  # trade speed for code size (e.g. use PyTuple_Pack())
+    needs_subexpr_cleanup = False  # set to True in code-generation if we

@@ -8179,14 +8187,26 @@ def generate_sequence_packing_code(self, code, target=None, plain=False):
                 else:
                     size_factor = ' * (%s)' % (c_mult,)
 
-        if self.type is tuple_type and (self.is_literal or self.slow) and not c_mult:
+        if ((self.type is tuple_type or self.type is list_type) and
+                (self.is_literal or self.slow) and
+                not c_mult and
+                len(self.args) > 0):
             # use PyTuple_Pack() to avoid generating huge amounts of one-time code
-            code.putln('%s = PyTuple_Pack(%d, %s); %s' % (
+            if self.type is list_type:
+                pack_name = '__Pyx_PyList_Pack'

+                    UtilityCode.load_cached('ListPack', 'ObjectHandling.c')

+                pack_name = 'PyTuple_Pack'
+            code.putln('%s = %s(%d, %s); %s' % (

                 code.error_goto_if_null(target, self.pos)))
             code.put_gotref(target, py_object_type)
+            self.needs_subexpr_cleanup = True

commit.message:
Add __Pyx_PyList_pack function

Analagous to "PyTuple_Pack" designed to be used in "slow" (i.e.
module-level) code. The main thing this catches are lists used in
"from something import name".

Also use `PyTuple_Pack` more thoroughly in module-level code.
The slow attribute of SequenceNode was never being set. This
probably affects tuples used in class construction like the bases
tuple, which isn't a literal.
